ing. This volume addresses many issues unique to Canada in a broader framework of global communications. Specifically, it looks at new media communications in Aboriginal communities, the changing role of the state in cultural institutions, the conglomeratization of the media, the threat of American and global communications to Canadian voices, and the struggle to retain and reclaim local and national identities in the face of globalization. With articles from academics and professionals across Canada, How Canadians Communicate, Vol.1 provides the most current perspectives on communication in Canada in a rapidly changing world of technology and global communication.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCommunication and culturezCanada. 0aInformation technologyxSocial aspectszCanada. 0aMass mediaxSocial aspectszCanada. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh1 aBakardjieva, Maria, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakardjieva, Maria, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBeaty, Bart, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCarlin, Vincent A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrow, Barbara A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDornan, Christopher, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHebert, M. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJennett, P. A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKhouri, Malek, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLongford, Graham D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPannekoek, Frits, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPannekoek, Frits, eeditor.4e